<div class="prose">
  <h2 id="what-are-skills">What are Skills?</h2>
  <p>Skills are project-level capability definitions that tell agents what they can do and how to do it. Each skill contains a <strong>name</strong>, a unique <strong>key</strong>, and a <strong>markdown body</strong> with the full instructions or reference material.</p>
  <p>Skills are shared resources — they live at the project level and can be assigned to multiple roles. Define a capability once and reuse it across your entire agent team.</p>

  <h2 id="creating-skills">Creating Skills</h2>
  <p>Every skill requires three fields:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Key</strong> — a unique identifier within the project (e.g., <code>code-review</code>, <code>write-tests</code>). Used for programmatic reference and remains stable even if you rename the skill.</li>
    <li><strong>Name</strong> — a human-readable display name</li>
    <li><strong>Markdown</strong> — the full content of the skill: instructions, examples, templates, or reference material that the agent receives as context</li>
  </ul>
  <p>You can also set an optional <strong>description</strong> (a short summary) and a <strong>category</strong> for organizing skills into groups.</p>

  <h2 id="keys-and-categories">Keys &amp; Categories</h2>
  <p>The <strong>key</strong> must be unique within the project. It serves as a stable identifier — even if you rename the skill later, references by key remain valid. Choose descriptive, kebab-case keys like <code>code-review</code> or <code>deploy-staging</code>.</p>
  <p><strong>Categories</strong> let you group related skills together — for example, "Engineering", "QA", or "Documentation". This makes it easier to browse and manage skills as your project grows.</p>

  <h2 id="built-in-vs-custom">Built-in vs. Custom</h2>
  <p>Master of Puppets ships with <strong>built-in skills</strong> that cover common agent capabilities. These provide a baseline so agents can be productive immediately out of the box. Built-in skills cannot be deleted.</p>
  <p><strong>Custom skills</strong> are ones you create for your specific project needs. They work identically to built-in skills but are tailored to your domain, codebase, or workflows.</p>
  <p>When a role is first configured with an adapter, Master of Puppets automatically assigns a set of default skills based on the role's context. You can then customize the skill set for each role as needed.</p>

  <h2 id="assigning-to-roles">Assigning to Roles</h2>
  <p>Skills are connected to roles through a join relationship. A role can have many skills, and a skill can be assigned to many roles — add or remove skills from any role at any time.</p>
  <p>When an agent executes a task, it receives the markdown content of its assigned skills as context. This means the skill body is the primary way you instruct agents on <em>how</em> to perform specific types of work.</p>
  <p>Both the skill and the role must belong to the same project. Each skill can only be assigned to a given role once.</p>

  <h2 id="linking-documents">Linking Documents</h2>
  <p>Skills can have <strong>documents</strong> attached to them. This lets you associate reference files, style guides, API specs, or any supporting material with a skill.</p>
  <p>Linked documents give agents additional context beyond the skill's markdown content — useful for large reference material that you want to manage separately rather than inlining into the skill body.</p>
</div>
